Lab Assignment Seven: Sequential Network Architectures

Business Understanding

This collection includes 34,686,770 Amazon reviews for 2,441,053 goods from 6,643,669 different customers, taken from the Stanford Network Analysis Project (SNAP). The dataset is available until March 2013 and spans 18 years. You may obtain the dataset from Kaggle by going to this link: https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/kritanjalijain/amazon-reviews/data

In order to ensure that the class distribution is consistent with the original dataset, we chose to work with a subset of 100,000 reviews due to the restricted processing capability of our computers. Three columns make up the structure of the dataset: "1" for negative reviews and "2" for positive reviews indicate the type of review in the first column (Target).

In this lab, we will create sequential network models for binary classification in order to forecast consumer happiness based on Amazon product ratings.

1.1. Preprocess and Tokenize (1 point)

Each of the 100,000 reviews in the prepared dataset is organized into three columns. These columns are arranged as follows:

Column 1 (review type): This column shows the consumer feedback and has values of 1 for bad reviews and 2 for positive reviews. It also provides the target classes.

Column 2: Review titles: The titles of each review are listed in this column.

Column 3 (review body): Each review's primary body content is found in this column.

Tokenization

The act of tokenizing a text document or phrase involves dividing it into smaller pieces called tokens that may be handled and examined in more detail later on. These tokens are often characters or words found in the dataset. It was discovered that 812 letters was the maximum character length. This equates to about 160 words per review, assuming a word length of five letters on average. In order to account for this range and preserve readability and coherence in the reviews, we have decided to set the MAX_ART_LEN option for tokenization to 160. After tokenizing every word in every review, each word was given a distinct number.

1.2. Metric and Explanation (1 point)

The F1-Score will be the main assessment parameter for this binary classification challenge. The F1-Score is a reliable statistic for unbalanced datasets since it represents the harmonic mean of accuracy and recall.

Precision can be defined as the ratio of accurately predicted positive observations to the total number of positive predictions.

Recall: The proportion of all observations in the actual class that were accurately predicted to be positive.

When the cost of false positives and false negatives is high, the F1-Score strikes a compromise between these two measures and offers a unified performance measure. For instance, in sentiment analysis, firms' decision-making processes may be misled if a bad review is predicted to be positive or vice versa.

Our approach will be applied to forecast consumer satisfaction levels based on Amazon product reviews. The graphic illustrates how balanced the dataset is. When the model misclassifies a negative sentiment evaluation as positive, it is known as a false positive. False positive predictions come at a high cost since they can force an organization to make poor decisions if it acts under the mistaken impression that a client is content when in fact they are not. The percentage of genuine positive predictions made for a given class out of all forecasts made for that class is known as precision.

1.3. Data Separation (1 point)

The dataset will be divided using Stratified 10-Fold Cross Validation. By ensuring that the percentage of positive and negative samples in each fold is the same, this strategy yields a more reliable assessment of the model's performance.

Stratified K-Fold: Divides the data into K folds, each of which has a distribution of classes that is balanced.

Rationale: This approach guarantees that the performance of our model is assessed equitably across various data subsets and mimics real-world situations where data is frequently unbalanced.

The stratifiedShuffle with an 80/20 split was used as the splitting method for our dataset. 20% was set aside for testing and the remaining 80% for training. By using a stratified technique, the split data is guaranteed to maintain the same class distribution as the source dataset. The data is split into training and testing sets at random thanks to the shuffling. This randomization aids in lowering variation and bias in the model's assessment. A nice balance between the size of the training set and the testing set is offered by the 80/20 split. It permits a reasonable quantity of data to be used for training the model, while also setting aside a substantial amount for assessment.

2. Modeling:

2.1. Sequential network models with CNN and transformer architectures

Four distinct sequential network models were trained in this section: two used CNN-1 and CNN-2 convolutional neural network designs, while the other two used transformer architectures. GloVe 6b pre-trained embeddings in 100 dimensions were applied. The models were gradually trained in order to reduce computing time and effectively attain convergence.

In[]:
%%time

EMBED_SIZE = 100
# the embed size should match the file you load glove from
embeddings_index = {}
f = open('glove.6B.100d.txt', encoding="utf-8")



# save key/array pairs of the embeddings
#  the key of the dictionary is the word, the array is the embedding
for line in f:
    values = line.split()
    word = values[0]
    coefs = np.asarray(values[1:], dtype='float32')
    embeddings_index[word] = coefs
f.close()

print('Found %s word vectors.' % len(embeddings_index))

# now fill in the matrix, using the ordering from the
#  keras word tokenizer from before
found_words = 0
embedding_matrix = np.zeros((len(word_index) + 1, EMBED_SIZE))
for word, i in word_index.items():
    embedding_vector = embeddings_index.get(word)
    if embedding_vector is not None:
        # words not found in embedding index will be ALL-ZEROS
        embedding_matrix[i] = embedding_vector
        found_words = found_words+1

print("Embedding Shape:",embedding_matrix.shape, "\n",
      "Total words found:",found_words, "\n",
      "Percentage:",100*found_words/embedding_matrix.shape[0])

A sequential network model with a convolutional neural network (CNN) architecture is called Mode 1 (CNN-1).

In[]:
NUM_CLASSES =1
from tensorflow.keras.optimizers import Adam

sequence_input = Input(shape=(MAX_ART_LEN,), dtype='int32')
# starting size: 1000
embedded_sequences = embedding_layer(sequence_input) # from previous embedding
x = Conv1D(32, 3, activation='relu')(embedded_sequences)

# after conv, size becomes: 1000-4=996
x = MaxPooling1D(3)(x)# after max pool, 996/5 = 199
x = Dropout(0.2)(x)
x = Conv1D(32, 3, activation='relu')(x)


# after convolution, size becomes 15 elements long
# Take the mean of these elements across features, result is 128 elements
x_mean = GlobalAveragePooling1D()(x) # this is the size to globally flatten

# Take the variance of these elements across features, result is 128 elements
x_tmp = Subtract()([x,x_mean])
x_std = GlobalAveragePooling1D()(x_tmp**2)

x = Concatenate(name='concat_1')([x_mean,x_std])

x = Dense(25, activation='relu')(x)

x = Dropout(0.2)(x)

preds = Dense(NUM_CLASSES, activation='sigmoid')(x)

model_xvec1 = Model(sequence_input, preds)

opt = Adam(learning_rate=0.0001, epsilon=0.0001, clipnorm=1)

# if representing as OHE, use categorical_crossentropy
# if representing the class as an integer, use sparse_categorical_crossentropy
model_xvec1.compile(loss='binary_crossentropy',
              optimizer=opt,
              metrics=['Precision'])

print(model_xvec1.summary())

# combine all the history from training together

# The transformer architecture
class TransformerBlock(Layer): # inherit from Keras Layer
    def __init__(self, embed_dim, num_heads, ff_dim, rate=0.2):
        super().__init__()
        # setup the model heads and feedforward network
        self.att = MultiHeadAttention(num_heads=num_heads,
                                      key_dim=embed_dim)

        # make a two layer network that processes the attention
        self.ffn = Sequential()
        self.ffn.add( Dense(ff_dim, activation='relu') )
        self.ffn.add( Dense(embed_dim) )

        self.layernorm1 = LayerNormalization(epsilon=1e-6)
        self.layernorm2 = LayerNormalization(epsilon=1e-6)
        self.dropout1 = Dropout(rate)
        self.dropout2 = Dropout(rate)

    def call(self, inputs, training):
        # apply the layers as needed (similar to PyTorch)

        # get the attention output from multi heads
        # Using same inpout here is self-attention
        # call inputs are (query, value, key)
        # if only two inputs given, value and key are assumed the same
        attn_output = self.att(inputs, inputs)

        # create residual output, with attention
        out1 = self.layernorm1(inputs + attn_output)

        # apply dropout if training
        out1 = self.dropout1(out1, training=training)

        # place through feed forward after layer norm
        ffn_output = self.ffn(out1)
        out2 = self.layernorm2(out1 + ffn_output)

        # apply dropout if training
        out2 = self.dropout2(out2, training=training)
        #return the residual from Dense layer
        return out2

class TokenAndPositionEmbedding(Layer):
    def __init__(self, maxlen, vocab_size, embed_dim):
        super().__init__()
        # create two embeddings
        # one for processing the tokens (words)
        self.token_emb = Embedding(input_dim=vocab_size,
                                   output_dim=embed_dim)
        # another embedding for processing the position
        self.pos_emb = Embedding(input_dim=maxlen,
                                 output_dim=embed_dim)

    def call(self, x):
        # create a static position measure (input)
        maxlen = tf.shape(x)[-1]
        positions = tf.range(start=0, limit=maxlen, delta=1)
        # positions now goes from 0 to 500 (for IMdB) by 1
        positions = self.pos_emb(positions)# embed these positions
        x = self.token_emb(x) # embed the tokens
        return x + positions

class GloveTokenAndPositionEmbedding(Layer):
    def __init__(self):
        super().__init__()
        # create two embeddings
        # one for processing the tokens, pretrained (words)
        self.token_emb = Embedding(len(word_index) + 1,
                            EMBED_SIZE,
                            weights=[embedding_matrix],# here is the embedding getting saved
                            input_length=MAX_ART_LEN,
                            trainable=False)

        # another embedding for processing the position
        self.pos_emb = Embedding(MAX_ART_LEN,
                                 EMBED_SIZE,
                                 input_length=MAX_ART_LEN,
                                 trainable=True
                                )

    def call(self, x):
        # create a static position measure (input)
        maxlen = tf.shape(x)[-1]
        positions = tf.range(start=0, limit=maxlen, delta=1)
        # positions now goes from 0 to 500 (for IMdB) by 1
        positions = self.pos_emb(positions)# embed these positions
        x = self.token_emb(x) # embed the tokens
        return x + positions

3. Exceptional Work:

To compare the pre-trained ConceptNet Numberbatch embedding with the pre-trained GloVe embedding.

In this section, we compared ConceptNet Numberbatch and GloVe, two pre-trained embedding approaches. In both approaches, words are represented in a 300-dimensional high-dimensional vector space. We included all of these embedding methods into our Model 1 (CNN1), which has a standard neural network-based design. Because Model 1 (CNN-1) requires less computing time than transformer-based models, we went with it.

Using Pre-trained ConceptNet Numberbatch and GloVe Embeddings

We'll import the GloVe embeddings, generate an embedding matrix, and incorporate it into our model.

# Load GloVe embeddings
def load_glove_embeddings(glove_file, embedding_dim=100):
    embeddings_index = {}
    with open(glove_file, 'r', encoding='utf-8') as f:
        for line in f:
            values = line.split()
            word = values[0]
            coefs = np.asarray(values[1:], dtype='float32')
            embeddings_index[word] = coefs
    return embeddings_index

glove_file = '/tmp/glove.6B/glove.6B.100d.txt'
embedding_dim = 100
glove_embeddings_index = load_glove_embeddings(glove_file, embedding_dim)

# Create embedding matrix
def create_embedding_matrix(word_index, embeddings_index, embedding_dim):
    embedding_matrix = np.zeros((len(word_index) + 1, embedding_dim))
    for word, i in word_index.items():
        embedding_vector = embeddings_index.get(word)
        if embedding_vector is not None:
            embedding_matrix[i] = embedding_vector
    return embedding_matrix

# Build the word index from the IMDb dataset

ConceptNet Numberbatch Embedding:

We will load ConceptNet Numberbatch embeddings, generate an embedding matrix, and incorporate it into our model.

In[]:
import requests, zipfile, io

# Download ConceptNet Numberbatch embeddings
url = "https://conceptnet.s3.amazonaws.com/downloads/2019/numberbatch/numberbatch-en-19.08.txt.gz"
r = requests.get(url)
z = zipfile.ZipFile(io.BytesIO(r.content))
z.extractall("/tmp")

# Load ConceptNet embeddings
def load_conceptnet_embeddings(conceptnet_file, embedding_dim=300):
    embeddings_index = {}
    with open(conceptnet_file, 'r', encoding='utf-8') as f:
        for line in f:
            if line.startswith(" "):
                continue
            values = line.split()
            word = values[0]
            coefs = np.asarray(values[1:], dtype='float32')
            embeddings_index[word] = coefs
    return embeddings_index

conceptnet_file = '/tmp/numberbatch-en-19.08.txt'
embedding_dim_cn = 300
conceptnet_embeddings_index = load_conceptnet_embeddings(conceptnet_file, embedding_dim_cn)

# Create embedding matrix
embedding_matrix_cn = create_embedding_matrix(word_index, conceptnet_embeddings_index, embedding_dim_cn)

Comparing the Performance of Embeddings

The models will be trained with both GloVe and ConceptNet embeddings, and F1-Scores will be used to compare the models' performances.

In[]:
# Train models and evaluate F1-Scores using Stratified K-Fold Cross Validation
f1_scores_glove = []
f1_scores_cn = []

for train_index, val_index in skf.split(x_train, y_train):
    x_train_fold, x_val_fold = x_train[train_index], x_train[val_index]
    y_train_fold, y_val_fold = y_train[train_index], y_train[val_index]

    # Train LSTM model with GloVe embedding
    lstm_model_glove = create_lstm_model_glove(embedding_dim, lstm_units)
    lstm_model_glove.fit(x_train_fold, y_train_fold, epochs=10, batch_size=32, validation_data=(x_val_fold, y_val_fold), verbose=0)
    # Calculate F1-Score for LSTM with GloVe
    y_pred_glove = (lstm_model_glove.predict(x_val_fold) > 0.5).astype("int32")
    f1_glove = f1_score(y_val_fold, y_pred_glove)
    f1_scores_glove.append(f1_glove)

    # Train LSTM model with ConceptNet embedding
    lstm_model_cn = create_lstm_model_cn(embedding_dim_cn, lstm_units)
    lstm_model_cn.fit(x_train_fold, y_train_fold, epochs=5, batch_size=32, validation_data=(x_val_fold, y_val_fold), verbose=0)
    # Calculate F1-Score for LSTM with ConceptNet
    y_pred_cn = (lstm_model_cn.predict(x_val_fold) > 0.5).astype("int32")
    f1_cn = f1_score(y_val_fold, y_pred_cn)
    f1_scores_cn.append(f1_cn)

# Visualization of F1-Scores for embeddings
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
plt.plot(f1_scores_glove, label='LSTM Model with GloVe Embedding F1-Scores')
plt.plot(f1_scores_cn, label='LSTM Model with ConceptNet Embedding F1-Scores')
plt.xlabel('Fold')
plt.ylabel('F1-Score')
plt.title('F1-Scores for LSTM Models with Different Embeddings')
plt.legend()
plt.show()

The models' F1-Scores employing GloVe and ConceptNet Numberbatch embeddings are compared in order to ascertain whether embedding is more appropriate for our particular use of sentiment analysis on IMDb movie reviews.
